            <abstract id="ref3" label="Abstract">The 
                <title render="italic">Hika</title> Archive consists of correspondence and manuscripts sent to 
                <title render="italic">Hika</title> editor Michael Kirchberger. Noted contributors to the magazine include Carol Bergé, Allen Ginsberg, and Jim Harrison.</abstract>
        </did>
        <custodhist id="ref5">
            <head>Provenance</head>
            <p>The 
                <title render="italic">Hika</title> correspondence was given to Fales by Michael Kirchberger.</p>
        </custodhist>
        <accessrestrict id="ref6">
            <head>Access Restrictions</head>
            <p>Open to researchers. Appointments are necessary to consult archive or manuscript materials.</p>
        </accessrestrict>
        <bioghist id="ref9">
            <head>Historical Note</head>
            <p>
                <title render="italic">Hika,</title> established in 1935, is Kenyon College's oldest, student-run literary magazine. Michael Kirchberger served as its editor in 1966-67.</p>
            <p>Sources:
                <lb/> Kenyon College: Student Life: Film and Media,(http://www.kenyon.edu/x11583.xml) Accessed November 23, 2009
                <lb/>
                <title render="italic">60 Years of Hika</title>, Kenyon College Archives, 1990.
                <lb/></p>
            <p></p>
        </bioghist>
        <scopecontent id="ref10">
            <head>Scope and Content Note</head>
            <p>The
                <emph render="italic">Hika </emph> Archive consists of one box of correspondence and manuscripts submitted to Hika editor Michael Kirchberger.</p>
        </scopecontent>
        <arrangement id="ref11">
            <head>Arrangement</head>
            <p>The 
                <title render="italic">Hika</title> Archive is arranged in alphabetical order by correspondent.</p>
